&\"#5F%F$F#" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Functions.  In this \+
exericse we study the basic properties of polynomials and rational fun
ctions.  Some revelant MAPLE commands will be   factor, expand, solve,
 fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn is how to define a
 function.  There are two ways, each with its own advantages and disad
vantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }{TEXT 282 2 "a " }
{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymbolic expression in x" }{TEXT -1 119 "
 in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colon before the =, th
is is always required when defining something.)  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define the same polynomial a
s " }{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on the variable x" }{TEXT -1 40 " in t
he following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "
