-1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 111 "Why do you think high school students are nev
er asked to remember the general formula for the roots of a cubic?" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 151 "We have a hard enough time getting the k
ids to learn their multiplication tables without counting on their fin
gers.  That would blow their fingers off." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Solving Equations in One Vari
able.   There are two different commands to direct Maple to solve an e
quation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 286 7 "fso
lve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They have different purposes.  Th
e " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " command attempts to find exact
 solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 289 1 "f" }{TEXT -1 116 "  is
 defined in terms of only one variable, there are several different wa
ys to direct Maple to solve the equation  " }{TEXT 290 5 "f  = " }
{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The following all cause Maple to solv
e the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "       solve(f);" 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 20 "      \+
 solve(f=0,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 349 "Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a \+
polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [rat
ios of integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact soluti
ons.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the so
lutions of  a polynomial can be found exactly, only the polynomial has
 solutions.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 78 "You can force Maple to report additional (approximate) so
lutions by using the " }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT -1 45 " command.  \+
(What does the \"f\" stand for?)  In" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "
addition, to forcing Maple to report approximate solutions, you can sp
ecify a field extension (typically real or complex) and require Maple \+
to look for solutions which fit in that field extension.  Also, one ca
n specify a range of x values and force" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }
{TEXT -1 75 " to only look for solutions in that specified range.  For
 example, compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "
> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x-x^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++?F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For each of the polynomials " }{XPPEDIT 
18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }{TEXT -1 9 " through " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 
"p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT -1 19 ", do the following:" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   solve for all exact roots whereever pos
sible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find all approximate
 roots to 10 decimal places, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "     c. \+
 factor each into linear factors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 106 "You will need to click on  [> in the to
olbar to obtain new execution lines just below the cursor position." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 55 "p1 := x^2-2;  solve(p1);  fsolve(p1);  factor(p1,real);" }}
